.TH LIME 1 "April 2026" "Lime 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lime \- LALR(1) parser generator
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lime
.RI [ options ]
.I grammar-file
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lime
is an LALR(1) parser generator that reads a grammar specification from
.I grammar-file
and produces C source code implementing a parser for that grammar.
It is derived from the Lemon parser generator and generates
reentrant, thread-safe parsers with a push-model interface.
.PP
Unlike yacc and bison which use a pull model (the parser calls the lexer),
Lime generates push parsers where the caller feeds tokens to the parser
one at a time.
The generated parser is contained in a single C source file with no
external dependencies beyond the C standard library.
.PP
The input grammar file uses the
.B .lime
file extension by convention.
Lime produces up to four output files based on the input filename:
.TP
.IB basename .c
The generated C parser source code.
.TP
.IB basename .h
A header file containing token number definitions (\fB#define\fR
constants) for use by the lexer.
.TP
.IB basename .out
A report file describing the parser states, conflicts, and actions.
Useful for debugging grammar issues.
.TP
.IB basename .sql
An SQL file describing the parser tables (only with
.BR \-S ).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-b
Print only the basis configurations in the report file, omitting
derived configurations.
This makes the
.B .out
file shorter and easier to read for large grammars.
.TP
.B \-c
Do not compress the action table.
By default, Lime compresses the action table to reduce generated
code size.
This option disables compression, which may improve parser speed
at the cost of larger tables.
.TP
.BI \-d " directory"
Write output files to
.I directory
instead of the current working directory.
.TP
.BI \-D " macro"
Define a preprocessor macro for use with
.B %ifdef
directives in the grammar file.
Multiple
.B \-D
options may be given.
.TP
.B \-E
Print the input file after preprocessing
.RB ( %ifdef / %ifndef / %endif
expansion) and exit.
Useful for debugging conditional grammar sections.
.TP
.B \-F
Format the grammar file consistently and write the result to a new
file.
The formatted file should be reviewed and manually renamed to
replace the original.
.TP
.BI \-f " value"
Ignored.
Placeholder for passing
.B \-f
compiler options through build systems.
.TP
.B \-g
Print the grammar without semantic actions and exit.
This produces a clean listing of all production rules.
.TP
.BI \-I " value"
Ignored.
Placeholder for passing
.B \-I
compiler options through build systems.
.TP
.B \-j
Generate an AOT-compiled (ahead-of-time) action table in a
separate
.IB basename _aot.c
file.
.TP
.B \-L
Lint mode.
Validate grammar and module directives, report errors, and exit
with the number of errors found.
No output files are generated.
.TP
.B \-l
Do not generate
.B #line
directives in the output C file.
By default, Lime inserts
.B #line
directives so that compiler error messages refer to line numbers
in the original grammar file.
.TP
.B \-m
Generate a makeheaders-compatible output file.
When this option is given, a separate
.B .h
header file is not produced; the token definitions are included
in the
.B .c
file in a format compatible with the makeheaders utility.
.TP
.B \-n
Generate snapshot initialization code in a separate
.IB basename _snapshot.c
file.
.TP
.BI \-O " value"
Ignored.
Placeholder for passing
.B \-O
compiler options through build systems.
.TP
.B \-p
Show conflicts that were resolved by precedence rules.
Normally, resolved conflicts are not reported.
This option is useful for verifying that precedence declarations
have the intended effect.
.TP
.BI \-P PREFIX
Override the parser symbol prefix.
By default, the generated parser exports identifiers starting with
.B Parse
(or the value of the
.B %name
directive if set in the grammar).
.B \-P
replaces this prefix at the command line, which is useful when
linking multiple generated parsers into the same binary without
editing the grammar files.
For example,
.B "\-PSqlParser"
produces
.BR SqlParserAlloc() ", " SqlParser() ", " SqlParserFree() ", "
and so on.
.TP
.B \-q
Quiet mode.
Do not generate the
.B .out
report file.
.TP
.B \-r
Do not sort or renumber states.
By default, Lime reorders states so that states with fewer
choices appear at the end, which helps reduce table size.
.TP
.B \-s
Print parser statistics to standard output after generation.
The statistics include the number of terminal and non-terminal
symbols, rules, states, conflicts, and action table size.
.TP
.B \-S
Generate an
.B .sql
file describing the parser tables in SQL format.
.TP
.BI \-T " template-file"
Use
.I template-file
as the parser template instead of the built-in
.BR limpar.c .
The template contains the runtime parser code with
.B %%
markers where Lime inserts generated content.
.TP
.BI \-U " macro"
Undefine a preprocessor macro, counteracting a previous
.B \-D
option or an
.B %ifdef
that would otherwise match.
.TP
.B \-V
Enable verbose conflict diagnostics with derivation paths.
When a conflict is reported, this option shows the chain of
productions that leads to the conflict.
.TP
.BI \-W " value"
Ignored.
Placeholder for passing
.B \-W
compiler options through build systems.
.TP
.B \-x
Print the version number and exit.
.TP
.B \-X
Run in lex-compiler mode (lexer subsystem M1 frontend).
Reads the input as a
.B .lex
source file, runs parse \(-> resolve \(-> pretty-print, and
writes the canonical
.B .lex
representation to standard output.
Used for syntax-checking and round-trip validation;
future milestones extend this to emit DFA tables and
generated C runtime code.
See
.BR lime_grammar (5)
and
.B docs/LEXER_DESIGN.md
for the
.B .lex
syntax.
.SH GRAMMAR FILE FORMAT
A grammar file consists of a sequence of production rules and
directives.
Rules define the grammar; directives configure parser behavior.
.PP
Production rules have the form:
.PP
.RS
.EX
nonterminal(alias) ::= symbol1(A) symbol2(B). { C code; }
.EE
.RE
.PP
The parenthesized aliases are optional and provide names for
referencing semantic values in the action code.
Each rule is terminated by a period.
.PP
See
.BR lime_grammar (5)
for a complete description of the grammar file syntax and all
supported directives.
.SH EXAMPLES
Generate a parser from a grammar file:
.PP
.RS
.EX
lime calc.lime
.EE
.RE
.PP
This produces
.BR calc.c ,
.BR calc.h ,
and
.BR calc.out .
.PP
Generate with statistics and no report file:
.PP
.RS
.EX
lime -s -q calc.lime
.EE
.RE
.PP
Define a macro and specify an output directory:
.PP
.RS
.EX
lime -DENABLE_JSON -d build/ grammar.lime
.EE
.RE
.PP
Validate a modular grammar without generating output:
.PP
.RS
.EX
lime -L grammar.lime
.EE
.RE
.PP
Preprocess and display the grammar after macro expansion:
.PP
.RS
.EX
lime -E grammar.lime
.EE
.RE
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.TP
.B 0
Successful parser generation with no errors or unresolved conflicts.
If
.B %expect
.I N
is declared, the exit status is 0 when exactly
.I N
conflicts are found.
.TP
.B 1
One or more errors occurred during parsing or code generation,
or there are unresolved shift/reduce or reduce/reduce conflicts
(unless suppressed by
.BR %expect ).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.B lime
does not use any environment variables.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I limpar.c
The default parser template file.
Lime searches for this file in the same directory as the
.B lime
executable unless overridden with
.BR \-T .
.SH "GENERATED PARSER API"
The generated parser provides the following C functions (where
.I Parse
is replaced by the
.B %name
directive value, defaulting to \(lqParse\(rq):
.TP
.BI "void *" Parse "Alloc(void *(*)(size_t));"
Allocate and return a new parser instance.
The argument is a memory allocation function (typically
.BR malloc (3)).
.TP
.BI "void " Parse "Free(void *, void (*)(void *));"
Deallocate a parser instance.
The second argument is a deallocation function (typically
.BR free (3)).
.TP
.BI "void " Parse "(void *, int, " TokenType ", " ExtraArg ");"
Feed a token to the parser.
The second argument is the token code (from the generated
.B .h
file), and the third is the token's semantic value.
The fourth argument is the extra argument declared by
.BR %extra_argument .
Feed token code 0 to signal end of input.
.TP
.BI "void " Parse "Trace(FILE *, char *);"
Enable parser tracing for debugging.
Each trace line is prefixed with the given string.
Pass
.B NULL
to disable tracing.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR lime_grammar (5),
.BR yacc (1),
.BR bison (1)
.SH AUTHORS
The Lemon parser generator was originally written by D. Richard Hipp
for the SQLite project.
Lime is an extended version of Lemon with support for modular
grammars, runtime extensions, and additional code generation features.
